The President-General of Kebbi State Igbo Community, Chief Nnamani has said that Igbos in the state stand for one indivisible Nigeria during and after elections. According to the traditional ruler, the concern of Igbos is a good leader who will be president for all Nigerians “we want a president for Igbos, Yoruba and Hausas a unified who will carry every tribe along and one who will give sound leadership. On the sidelines chief Nnamani stated that, now that some prominent Igbos have declared presidential interest, the Igbo community in Kebbi will support any good candidate from Igbo extraction that is able to win his party ticket come 2023 general election. On Igbos’ host community relationship, the Igbo leader declared that Igbos in Kebbi are no longer any indigenes as every Friday they pay royal homage to the emir of Gwandu his royal highness Muhammadu Iliyasu Bashar who gives them some advice to those who comes for same royal homage so he always gives them the sense of belonging and strength to move freely and do lawful businesses without any hitch in Kebbi state. However, following the death of Eze Igbo and subsequent appointment of chief Emeka Okafor the president-general said such nearly divided the Igbos in the state but the timely intervention of his royal highness Muhammadu Illiyasu Bashar has calmed nerves as he set up a committee to look into the issue “I am not in a position to speak on the issue of the new Eze Igbo only the chairman can” he urged his members to remain law-abiding while thanking the governor of Kebbi state Senator Atiku Bagudu Nnamani pledged the support of the Igbo community in ensuring peace and unity continue to prevail in the state.